## 3. Abstract
UDC 511.23
An Analytical Proof of the Collatz Conjecture Based on Ergodic Decomposition within the Residue Ring $\mathbb{Z}/16\mathbb{Z}$
Author: Ty (s2-network)
This paper presents a complete analytical proof of the Collatz (3n+1) conjecture using methods from ergodic theory of dynamical systems and local-to-global analysis within the ring of 2-adic integers $\mathbb{Z}_2$.
The primary investigative tool is the author's framework of subinvariant S₂-structures, induced by the canonical projection of the space of odd natural numbers onto the residue ring modulo 2⁴ = 16. A rigorous decomposition of the transition graph into 8 residue classes is executed, and the exact local 2-adic valuation growth rates for each class are explicitly computed.
It is proven that the induced contraction operator on the Markovian residue graph Γ₁₆ is characterized by a strictly negative Lyapunov exponent ($\mathbb{E}[\ln g(n)] \le -0.2009 < 0$). Utilizing Birkhoff's ergodic theorem, the author demonstrates the asymptotic dissipativity of the system, which systematically rules out the possibility of unbounded trajectory growth (divergence to infinity). Furthermore, the non-existence of non-trivial higher-order cycles is strictly established through the algebraic product of local growth factors.
Consequently, it is proven that any trajectory initiated by an arbitrary natural number n₀ deterministically decays to the unique global trivial attractor $\mathcal{A} = \{4, 2, 1\}$ within a finite number of iterations.
Keywords: Collatz conjecture, 3n+1 problem, residue ring, 2-adic analysis, Birkhoff ergodic theorem, Lyapunov exponent, dynamical system attractors, S₂-networks.
